Promoters record increasing bookings
It looks like it 's going to be a good winter for German tour operators:
According to one study, the turnover of travel bookings for the coming months compared to the previous year has increased significantly - for the winter season even by more than 30%.
Despite weak economic prospects, the desire to travel among Germans remains strong, according to one survey.
Travel agencies recorded a 31% increase in winter season bookings compared with the same period last year, the German tourism association DRV reported in Berlin on Monday.
According to the survey by the market research institute GfK, booking quotas are already increasing for the autumn months.
The surplus of travel agencies for October compared to 2007 would therefore amount to about 11%, the DRV reported.
The figures are based on the figures of the GfK, which analyses booking data from 1200 German travel agencies on a monthly basis and draws up statistical projections for the entire market.
It would also include travel bookings made up to the end of August 2008.
Due to the weak dollar, travel to the United States would be particularly in demand, the DRV reported.
Here the increase in bookings would amount to about a third.
In addition, Spain, Turkey, Greece and locations within Germany would be particularly popular travel destinations for Germans.
All-inclusive travel is particularly popular, explained DRV President Klaus Laepple.
Given the rising costs of energy and foodstuffs, the costs in this case would be 'better calculable for customers than for an individually organised holiday'.
Consumers could save money through, among other things, discounts on bookings made well in advance or all-inclusive offers, Laepple explained.
The summer months would also have been a good year for bookings, with a surplus in turnover again compared to the previous year - although according to a further study the number of Germans taking a trip fell compared to the previous year.
