Turkey is expanding its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to join the European Union, European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps into Asia, lies one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the tour guides tell you.
The building sits between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking out at the world like some German provincial town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the ceiling to the vault, there was no doubt about the greatness of the enterprise of what was the farthest passage to the west.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a latecomer to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions of dominating the Middle East by means of this railway that ran from Damascus to Baghdad and beyond into what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany's imperial ambitions were dashed during World War I.
His railroads were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
The isolation of the region from the surrounding region, created by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed.
British and dominant forces advanced out of Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for the station in Hyderpasha too.
In 1917 a munitions train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has been slowly decaying, largely outdated by history.
But today, this railway outlet to Anatolia and all the points to the east, serve - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's ever-widening diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, is over.
Now there's a new policy of engagement.
The Turkish government has remarkably good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To assess the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the sleeping car to the Turkish capital Ankara to visit one of the leading experts on foreign policy of the AKP, the Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a bouncing race down the tracks that produced the old world rhythms of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital - proposed as a new city for a secular state intent on turning its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in the Turkish consensus.
It has suggested some suspicion in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built on purpose - in a developing suburb, surrounded by medium-sized shopping malls and power pastry shops, where business executives in suits - both men and women - meet to make contracts early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Complete, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry too.
"The foreign policy party's goal now is to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbors.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he tells me.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today, you must look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't one or the other.
It must be both.
"But surely at some point", I ask, "will Turkey be forced to decide?"
"Turkey", he says, "does not want to face that choice".
It also points out a point that almost everyone I have spoken to here has memorized: the links of the European Union not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, the whole of Europe can metaphorically travel along those railway lines eastward through Asia and into the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after another night of no light, I think of those two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would be to find that Europe's Middle East ambitions may now be largely in the hands of Turkey.
And as I wait at the terminal for the ferry that will take me back across the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
At least then there seemed to be no doubt as to which continent should lay claim to this fascinating country.
