The Bee Car to Avoid Collisions
In developing accident prevention technologies, Nissan has taken inspiration from nature, and in particular bees.
A Japanese company has created a robot that can avoid accidents by taking the flight of bees, for example.
It's the Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step towards collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at the Advanced Technology Center at Nissan Motor Co. developed this small robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Brand Management Development, the BR23C is an extension of the four-area Safety Shield produced by Nissan.
This robot is intended to improve the ability to prevent collisions in the manufacturer's vehicles.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space that is very similar to the Nissan safety shield.
But most important are the bees' compound eyes, which can see in all directions at an angle of over 300 degrees, and which allow the insect to fly uninterruptedly in its personal space.
To recreate this visual feature, engineers have developed what they call a laser location finder.
This mechanism detects obstacles that are in front of the BR23C within a radius of two meters and with a maximum amplitude of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to a onboard microprocessor that immediately, allows to prevent the collision.
"The minute it detects an obstacle, the little robot mimics the movements of a bee and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels at right angles or higher to avoid a collision.
The most obvious difference with any assisted system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
"If it were not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot veer up or down, not even diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction in which its wheels can turn, and not by exploiting infinite directions and ways as bees do.
For this reason, Nissan used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot could avoid collisions.
"This device only needs to process the information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It does not require the storage of information or the intuitive logic of previous maneuvers, so it can run without interruption and with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may come as a surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or megabyte".
It is the first step towards developing new technologies for instant collision prevention, a technology that Nissan hopes will be standard in cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion type.
Another potential future application of this technology could be the integration of the units with a GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to their destination while avoiding obstacles along the way.
