The Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux countries are helping the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first bank in Europe to be in difficulty as a result of the US credit crisis, by partially nationalising it. The three countries will provide EUR 11.2 billion to the financial and insurance institution, which also has interests in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands reached agreement at the highest level over the weekend, including the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
The first major crisis in the euro area in the context of the difficulties which have been plaguing the international financial market for more than a year was that of Fortis Bank, and in some respects the decisions taken in this respect may set a precedent.
Under the decision taken on Sunday night, all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank's stake in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell some of its interests, including first and foremost the assets, mainly insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week Fortis' shares began a vertical slump, with serious signs of the firm's crisis emerging in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too big to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank's stock fell almost 12 percent on Friday, its lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of the shares has fallen by more than two thirds.
At current share prices, the total capital value of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the bank's executives this value is not real.
The company's top executives attribute the collapse in Fortis stock to uncertainties in the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US $700 billion plan.
On Monday, the stock slowly picked up.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed as the new CEO of the bank.
The financial institution has also sought private buyers but so far no one has come up with a worthy offer.
The Belgian Government had previously assured investors that they should not fear losing their money.
The bank's customers did not panic, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing companies.
The Fox in the Chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on people's medical purchase records, often refuse to take out insurance.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a privacy program where the use of prescription data is always subject to the consent of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, or it is like leaving the chicken coop to the fox". - quoting Richard Dick, author of the prescription drug program, as writing in The Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of claims dependent on the health of the prospective customer and, if they consider the risk too high, do not insure.
In the past, the customer had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was only concluded after the examination.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure 10 years ago: the customer's ID code allows you to easily get information from pharmacies about which medicines you have bought in the last year and a half and from this the program can tell you what diseases you have and what your health condition is.
For example, if you regularly buy large amounts of cholesterol lowering drugs, this means that your blood fat level is practically incurably high and you are classified in the highest risk category.
There are various versions of the programme on the market, some of which also determine the risk multiplier, so the insurer does not have much to do with paperwork, although there are some minor difficulties.
The downside is that some medicines can be used for multiple purposes, e.g. some compounds are used for migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from the insurance-commercial point of view, is a factor of risk, the first two are not.
Separate companies have been set up for the purpose of requesting and processing data and they ask for the patient's consent before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies.
Now the authorities force them to do so even though they have not yet imposed fines for negligence.
Some companies are also processing lab results and linking them to drug consumption data to provide a more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to data and at the same time it will become increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is a separate privacy law but it only applies to healthcare and insurance.
The Commission has already proposed a new law to give the authorities the power to supervise data service companies.
Richard Dick admits that this is not enough: he has therefore developed a programme which links the transmission of data to the consent of the person concerned.
The Commission has already made a number of proposals to this effect.
So in the end the chickens are left to the mercy of the fox.
