EU and India double trade
As the EU and India are trading partners, the ninth summit's agenda was dominated by this issue, as well as all other global issues.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit which will deal primarily with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognises that India is becoming a major democratic power which should have a greater say in international affairs, but the Member States have not yet been able to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So this question was not raised at the ninth summit in Marseilles yesterday.
The French President, Nicolas Sarkozy, as President-in-Office of the Union, José Manuel Barroso, President of the Commission, and Javier Solana, High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they reached an agreement to double trade in five years, i.e. to increase it to EUR 100 billion.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods rose from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an ambitious goal.
The result is that the 26 bilateral civil aviation agreements have been legally unified, so that air traffic can also take off in the future.
India would like to sign the Free Trade Agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the deal.
The aim is to balance this, because while the EU is India's number one trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among EU partners.
The summit focused on global issues.
They called for the establishment of a UN conference on the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and on terrorism, which was condemned in all its forms by both sides.
They called for the conclusion of the Doha Trade Round, even though both sides played a role in its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will continue to pursue its energy and climate agenda, which aims to reduce emissions by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agrees with this, and that a global pact should be agreed at the climate conference next year to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 50 percent by 2050.
They also want to curb the rise in food prices and have supported the convening of an international meeting to examine the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister will travel to the French capital today where he is preparing to sign a treaty on the peaceful use of atomic energy at a bilateral meeting.
